definition.value: An estuary which is composed primarily of brackish water.

value.value: A piece of rock which is derived from clastic rock and has a grain size of 4 to 64 millimeters.

definition.value: The grain size classification is based on the Krumbein phi scale of sedimentology.

value.value: A piece of rock which has a grain size between 64 and 256 mm.
The liquid produced when water percolates through any permeable material. It can contain either dissolved or suspended material, or usually both.
A calcic spring through which groundwater, heated by geothermal energy, flows.

definition.value: A solid surface layer which 1)  forms part of the boundary between the cavity of a cave and its solid container and 2) is roughtly perpendicular to the cave floor.
Soil which has elevated concentrations of chromate.
Soil which has elevated concentrations of xylene.
Coal mine lake sediment is lake sediment which covers the bottom of a coal mine lake.
Water which has physicochemical properties that have been determined by the processes occuring in a sea or ocean.
This definition refers to water that is actually in a sea or ocean. This water may have a wide range of salinity levels.
Coastal sea water is sea water that is adjacent to a coast.

The limits of what qualifies as "adjacent to" vary greatly. This should be defined on a data level and is left intentionally fuzzy here. The label is "coastal sea water" rather than "coastal water" as some large lakes are often said to have coasts.

value.value: A bioreactor which captures and, through the biological processes maintained in the medium it contains, degrades pollutants.
A biofilter which contains compost and avails of the microbial communities within it to degrade pollutants.
A highly contaminated site designated by the United States of America's Comprehensive Environmental Response, Compensation, and Liability Act.

definition.value: Mud which is part of an estuary.

value.value: A solid environmental material which is formed by the replacement of organic substances (including those in soils and sediments) with mineral material.
Manure which has been derived from the aerobically decomposed remnants of organic materials.
A hospital is a building in which health care services are  provided by specialized staff and equipment.

label.value: iron-reducing zone of petroleum contaminated sediment

definition.value: A zone within a portion of petroleum contaminated sediment within which iron-reducing processes occur.
Organically enriched sediment which has increased levels of naphthalene.

value.value: A neutral spring through which groundwater, heated by geothermal energy, flows.

definition.value: Organically enriched sediment which has increased levels of nitrobenzene.

value.value: A manufactured container within which oil or other petrochemical products are stored and which these products are usually transported to end users or further storage facilities.

definition.value: A landform which is located under the surface of a landmass.
A subsurface landform which contains fluid hydrocarbons in porous or fractured rock formations.

value.value: Straw or other material strewn in an animal's enclosure (e.g. a stable) for it to sleep on and to absorb its faeces and urine.
An aquarium is a vivarium which simulates the submerged portions of an aquatic environment
